`crates/ctx-cage` is the sandboxing crate: it isolates an autonomous agent
run's filesystem, namespaces, and network egress, while `ctx-context`
handles content filtering and tool brokering. Depending on this crate
buys a caged process with no direct API-key exposure, offline-by-default
DNS, and a real-host-path bind of the target root — never a fixed alias.

`src/` is the implementation: CLI parsing, lifecycle orchestration
(prepare→run→teardown), bwrap arg construction, the egress proxy, and the
single `CageError` type. `assets/` supplies the static files it embeds
and mounts — `cage-nsswitch.conf`/`cage-resolv.conf` for the offline
netns, `cage-rules.md` for agent-session prompting. `tests/` is the
behavioral spec, exercising the public surface (`bwrap::build_bwrap_args`,
`lifecycle::load_cagevars`, `cli::resolve_mode`, `proxy`) against real
tempfiles and sockets rather than mocks.

Two ADRs cut across all three subtrees and must stay mutually consistent
wherever touched: ADR-046 (real host-path binding, not `/work`) and
ADR-049 (offline stub `resolv.conf` with at least one non-loopback
nameserver despite being unreachable). Editing the resolv.conf asset
requires checking `src/bwrap/` and `tests/bwrap_build.rs`/`cage_assets.rs`
together. The crate-wide invariant — real API key never enters the cage
process, only `proxy.rs` injects it host-side — is enforced by `src/` and
verified end-to-end by `tests/`; `assets/` is inert data with no runtime
enforcement of its own. Billed-mode gating (`--allow-spend`, clean git
tree, proxy start order, `ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL` injection) must stay
agreed across `cli.rs`, `lifecycle/prepare.rs`, `lifecycle/run.rs`, and
`lifecycle/env.rs`.

No `intent.md` is present for this directory.